h3. Problem Definition

Create a report of all user that have not reported Issues and allow them to be deleted.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2825].
  {panel}

While reindexing isn't a frequent operation (should never really be necessary), it does take a long time for large numbers of issues.  On a 2.6Ghz box, reindexing 5000 issues takes 562 seconds (9 mins).  Need to look into whether this can be optimized.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2822].
  {panel}

It'd be nice if you could multi-select the versions you wanted to release in bulk, instead of having to release each version one at a time.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2819].
  {panel}

Edited a Link Type by removing the values in the Link, Outward Link Description and Inward Link Description fields and selected Update. The system allowed the link type to be submitted with no properties at all.  I believe the system should prevent this from happening.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2815].
  {panel}

It would be nice to be able to have a entry similar to a version that shows unscheduled items. For small, low volume projects, unscheduled items tend to get overlooked since the developer tends to focus on the Road Map. This would need to be a on per-project basic since not all project are low-volume.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2814].
  {panel}

Right now if I need a different notification target for each project, I need to create a new notification scheme for every project.  This is particularly laborious in an environment like the ASF JIRA installation where you may have 100+ projects, each needing a different target, and while I would like the notification scheme to represent the *types* of notifications that go out, I instead have to create 100+ notification schemes just because the target is different for each.

If we could have a project-level attribute(s) that the notification could pull from, then I could create notification schemes only per "scheme" and not per target.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2797].
  {panel}

attachments should be compress on the fly, based on mime-type and/or file extension...

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2794].
  {panel}

So that it can be viewed by text viewers as well as HTML viewers.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2785].
  {panel}

Have the ability to hide inactive projects.

Once an application has reached the end of it's life, we would like the ability to hide it from the list of project.  We don't want to delete it and lose all the issues (in case we need to go back), but we don't want new issues to be put against it.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2765].
  {panel}

Project leads many times want to go through all the issues, read them, and then assign them, or schedule them.

Bulk editing helps; however, it only works in the "browser" view. If it was possible to do bulk editing in the "full content" view, then users can select the issues to be edited as they read them, basing their selection on the content of the issue.

Otherwise, they can only make their selection based on the summary of the issue.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2753].
  {panel}

JIRA supports the ability to customise the workflow by defining new actions but there is no way of applying security to these actions by the use of permissions.

What is required is the ability to define custom permissions which can be checked by the workflow. For example:
If the workflow defines a custom action "Promote Issue to Test" then there should be an associated permission called "Promote Issues to Test" so that only users with the appropriate permission can execute the action.  Currewently the interim workaround is to allow only the current assignee to exceute any custom actions.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2744].
  {panel}

As well as version information for projects, it would be good to be able to track version numbering for components, which may have different version migration paths from the overall project.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2735].
  {panel}

{panel:title=Atlassian Update - 19 March 2015|borderStyle=solid|borderColor=#ebf2f9 | titleBGColor=#ebf2f9 | bgColor=#ffffff}
Thanks everyone for your feedback. After consideration, we are closing this issue because we do not expect to address it in the foreseeable future. As is clear from the examples below, the ideal propagated action depends on the type of issue link and varies depending on your use case. Considering issue links can be arbitrarily defined, this would require adding logic in JIRA to handle certain types of links differently from others. Alternatively, we would need to add settings to configure propagated actions based on the issue links.

Our belief is that the value doees not justify the expected increase in UI complexity or maintenance burden.

As always, please don't hesitate to contact me if you have any questions.

Thanks
Dave Meyer
Product Manager, JIRA Platform
{panel}


When an issue is linked as solved by or set as duplicate do a cascading update when resolving the issue that solves the duplicate.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2730].
  {panel}

Please add an "All voters" group which can be added to the notification list for issue changes.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2682].
  {panel}

For people translating JIRA is very interesting to know all changes made in i18n component.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2679].
  {panel}

Associating a project with a scheme should be just as easy as associating a scheme with a project.  This is not currently the case.

Say I've created a Notification/Permission/IssueField scheme, and now want to associate a project with it.  There is a 'projects' column sitting there waiting to be filled in, but there's no "Add" button that would let me quickly add the project.  I have to go "Projects" in the left-hand menu, find the project(s), and associate the scheme with them.  This is annoying, considering that schemes are typically created *after* projects.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2667].
  {panel}

Real trivial nit-pick one for you :)

When you go to resolve an issue, you see the text 'If you have permission to close issues, you can optionally resolve & close the issue at the same time'.

Jira knows whether or not you have this permission so should provide meaningful text for each case.  Secondly, how does this text work with a custom work flow...?

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2645].
  {panel}

Similar to JRA-2644, but from a different angle. Instead of focusing on extending what users get regarding project notifications - allowing them to turn things off.

EG: No matter what, I dont want to recieve emails about comments on any project ... or I dont want to recieve notifications at all as I am going on holiday and will catch up later.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2641].
  {panel}

Say I search JIRA n times a day.  For (n-1) searches, I will have a saved search in my session.  This means I end up on the 'View' filter tab, which doesn't have any search fields.

This is all fine, *if* my last search is relevant to me.  However, on average, it isn't.  This means I have to click on the 'Edit' tab to get anything useful.

Couldn't the extra info and links on the 'View' page be squeezed onto the top of the 'Edit' page?

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2639].
  {panel}

Add a way to add custom project properties. These could be of type string (<255 characters), text, number, boolean, date.

The value of these properties could be set/used by jelly scripts for example.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2635].
  {panel}

We currently have two instances of Jira running, but will hopefully be adding more in the future.  This allows different teams to have different customisations etc.  However, it would be great to be able to share users between the installations, as some people span multiple groups.

I guess this could be achieved with the external user management system?

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2634].
  {panel}

One of our users has asked if we can permission more than one group to view comments.  For example, they have separate groups for Project Managment, Developer and User roles.  Some of the comments are for internal viewing only - i.e. for PM and Developer - so they would like to be able to restrict permissions to only those groups.  Currently this can only be done on a project-wide basis.

For the moment, I have added the PMs to the developer group so they can see comments permissioned for the developers, but it feels like this would be a useful feature going forward.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2627].
  {panel}

Over the course of a release, various small bugs get discovered that can be fixed by a patched JSP or class.  Typically these patches are attached to a jira.atlassian.com bugreport, and users can download and apply the change locally.  It would be nice to have a patch system, whereby approved patches can be automatically downloaded and applied.

A simple Ant-based system is described at:

http://aft.sourceforge.net/updates.html

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2589].
  {panel}

Difficult to determine whether issues has already been logged.  It would be great if as you entered key words in the summary field, JIRA displayed issues with the same words or text to assist with determining whether a defect exist or not.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2581].
  {panel}

Because we use the projects to manage our unapproved change requests/requirements, I need the ability to migrate approved requests/requirements over to our development project at the point where we have received said approval. I'd like to keep a copy of the original issue in both places so that our project mgrs can track the issue in their project and our developers can track the issue separately in their project (they may want to change the issue type, priority, etc).  

Would like to have the ability to make updates to the issue appear on both copies or on just one copy. 

Would like to keep this separate from moving, which causes the issue to lose its original numbering and which takes it completely out of a project, or linking, which simply links related/duplicated issues.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2563].
  {panel}

When linking an issue, the comment provided becomes associated with both issues in the general "Comments" field. It seems as though it would be more intuitive if the link comment was moved into the "Issue Links:" field on the web page.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2522].
  {panel}

when I reindex the database (necessary whenever doing bulk updates via sql), it affects all users in the system at the time -- nobody can search while the index is being rebuilt. it would be better/safer to build new indexes in a new location and do a quick swap-out of the old ones, to minimize impact on end-users.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2512].
  {panel}

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2484].
  {panel}

As the use of JIRA grows in a large company, inevitably teams will want to branch off and have their own installations of JIRA (we hope anyway).  Inevitably also, managers cannot resist tinkering with their organisations, with teams often moving around within the company.

Therefore, at some point we will want to move projects from one installation to another.  Whilst it's easy to split a large JIRA into smaller JIRAs, merging two is not so easy.

So, wouldn't it be great to be able to point one JIRA instance at another and move projects / permission schemes / users etc between them using SOAP or similar?  Our need for this is not immediate, but the time will come very soon when this could become a bit of a problem.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-2468].
